"Valdez B., Schorr M., Quintero M., García R., Rosas N.","Effect of climate change on durability of engineering materials in hydraulic infrastructure: An overview",2010,"Corrosion Engineering Science and Technology","45","1",,"34","41",,,10.1179/147842209X12559428167526,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77749330168&partnerID=40&md5=bdfc30ebea82a34ede18f9a79222fd03","Red Nacional de Corrosion, Instituto de Ingenieria, Universidad Autonoma de Baja California, Blvd. Benito Juarez s/n, CP 21280, Mexicali, Baja California, Mexico; Universidad Politécnica de Baja California, Mexicali, Baja California, Mexico","Valdez, B., Red Nacional de Corrosion, Instituto de Ingenieria, Universidad Autonoma de Baja California, Blvd. Benito Juarez s/n, CP 21280, Mexicali, Baja California, Mexico; Schorr, M., Red Nacional de Corrosion, Instituto de Ingenieria, Universidad Autonoma de Baja California, Blvd. Benito Juarez s/n, CP 21280, Mexicali, Baja California, Mexico; Quintero, M., Red Nacional de Corrosion, Instituto de Ingenieria, Universidad Autonoma de Baja California, Blvd. Benito Juarez s/n, CP 21280, Mexicali, Baja California, Mexico; García, R., Red Nacional de Corrosion, Instituto de Ingenieria, Universidad Autonoma de Baja California, Blvd. Benito Juarez s/n, CP 21280, Mexicali, Baja California, Mexico; Rosas, N., Universidad Politécnica de Baja California, Mexicali, Baja California, Mexico","The hydraulic infrastructure is constituted by the assets of two central elements: water supply and energy generation facilities. This study deals with the durability of the structures and their engineering materials. Four vital parts of this infrastructure were selected: dams, canals, aqueducts and hydroelectric stations, which are built of two basic materials; steel and concrete. The global climate change and warming and the greenhouse - gas emissions (all interrelated complex phenomena) affect these construction materials and structures, mainly by their extreme events such as torrential rains and flooding, dry and wet seasons, high and low humidity and solar radiation. This study presents a general global approach to the climate influence on the durability of those materials and structures and concludes with a description of a particular region: a section of the 'Great American Desert' on the Mexico-USA border. © 2010 Institute of Materials, Minerals and Mining.","Climate change; Concrete; Corrosion; Hydraulic infrastructure; Steel","Concrete corrosion; Construction materials; Dry and wet; Energy generations; Engineering materials; Extreme events; Global climate changes; Greenhouse-gas emissions; Hydroelectric station; Low humidity; Me-xico; Torrential rain; Building materials; Corrosion; Durability; Gas emissions; Hydraulic structures; Hydraulics; Hydroelectric power plants; Leakage (fluid); Sun; Water supply; Climate change",,,,,,"Easterling, D.R., Meehl, G.A., Parmesan, C., Changnon, S.A., Karl, T.R., Mearns, L.O., Climate extremes: Observations, modelling and impacts' (2000) Science, 289, pp. 2068-2074; Dimontakis, P.E., Global change and energy: A path forward (2008) Eng. Sci. Winter, 71 (4), pp. 12-19; Contribution of Working Group 1 to the Fourth Assessment Report of Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, 966. , S. Solomon, D. Qin, M. Manning, Z. Chen, M. Marquis, K. B. Averyt, M. Tignor and H. L. Miller (eds) . Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; Cameron, C., Catovsky, S., Crane, D., Cruickshank, S., Edmondson, N., Garbutt, S., Hamid, M.L., Zenghelis, D., (2007) The Economics of Climate Change: The Stem Review', 692. , Cambridge, Cambridge University Press; Walsh, B., How to win the war on global warming (2009) Time Magazine, , 25 May; Lioubimtseva, E., Adams, J.M., Possible implications of increased carbon dioxide levels and climate change for desert ecosystoms (2004) Environ. Manag., 33, pp. 388-404; Lagerloef, G., (2009) EOS, 90 (18), p. 157; Quintero-Nuñez, M., Sweedler, A., (2004) Imperial-Mexicali Valley: De